<section xml:id="xy-plots">
<title>2D Plots</title>

	<objectives>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				By the end of this section, you will be able to ...
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<ol>
			<li>plot points in MATLAB.</li>
			<li>add basic customization options to your plot.</li>
		</ol>
	</objectives>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			In this section, we discuss the graphics capabilities of Matlab.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<p>
		The main commands that we will use in this chapter are
	</p>

	<p>
		<c>plot</c>, <c>subplot</c>, <c>figure</c>, and <c>hold</c> 
	</p>

	<p>
		and the customizations
	</p>

	<p>
		<c>xlim</c>, <c>ylim</c>, <c>xlabel</c>, <c>ylabel</c>, and <c>title</c>
	</p>

	<p>
		Plots in Matlab are created by simply "connecting the dots."  This means that you have to provide the actual coordinates of the points (both the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> coordinates).  It is not enough to simply say plot <m>y=x^2</m>, you must give <insert>exactly</insert> which <m>x</m> values you want squared. 
	</p>
	
	<paragraphs xml:id="basic-plotting">
	<title><insert>Basic Plotting</insert></title><p/>

		<example xml:id="example_basicplot">
		<title><em>Basic Plot</em></title>

			<p>
				Suppose we wanted to plot the points
				<me>(1,4), (2,15), (3,7), (4,17), (5,8), (6,19), (7,20), (8,21), (9,22), (10,23).</me>
			</p>

			<p>
				Give the commands that
				<ol label="a">
					<li>define the vector, <c>x</c>, as the <m>x</m> values of the points above.</li>
					<li>define the vector, <c>y</c>, as the <m>y</m> values of the points above.</li>
					<li>plot these points.</li>
				</ol>
			</p>

			<sidebyside>
				<p>
					<sage language="octave">
						<input>
							x = ?;  
							y = ?;
							?
						</input>
					</sage>
				</p>
			</sidebyside>

			<solution>
				<p>
					We first define <c>x</c> and <c>y</c> as vectors. Notice that we make use of the colon operator when we can.

					<aside>
						<p>
							For plotting, it doesn't matter if <c>x</c> or <c>y</c> are row or column vectors. 
						</p>
					</aside>

					<sidebyside width="100%">
						<program language="matlab">
							<input>
								x = [1:10];  
								y = [4 15 7 17 8 19:23];
							</input>
						</program>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					Then to plot the corresponding points, connected by line segments, use
				</p>

				<sidebyside width="100%">
					<program language="matlab">
						<input>
							plot(x,y)
						</input>
					</program>
				</sidebyside>

				<p>
					That's all you do.  The resulting plot is
				</p>

				<image source="figures/matlab_plot1.png" />
			</solution>
		</example>

		<p>
			Let's take the last example and add some customization.
		</p>

	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs xml:id="customizing-plots">
	<title><insert>Customizing Plots</insert></title><p/>

		<example xml:id="example_labelplot"><p/>
		<title><em>Plot with labels</em></title><p/>

			<p>
				In the command box below, type in the following commands and press the <kbd>Run Commands</kbd> <em>to see the effect each change has on the plot</em>. 
				<ul>
					<li>On line 2, add the command <c>plot(x,y,'LineWidth',3)</c></li> 
					<li>Change line 2 to <c>plot(x,y,'--','LineWidth',3)</c></li>
					<li>Change line 2 to <c>plot(x,y,'--&gt;','LineWidth',3)</c></li>
					<li>Change line 2 to <c>plot(x,y,'--&gt;b','LineWidth',3)</c></li>
					<li>On line 3, add the command <c>title('My plot')</c></li> 
					<li>On line 4, add the command <c>xlim([0,11])</c></li> 
					<li>On line 5, add the command <c>ylim([0,30])</c></li> 
					<li>On line 6, add the command <c>text(7,15,'My function')</c></li> 
				</ul>
			
			</p>
			
			<sidebyside>
				<p>
					<sage language="octave">
						<input>
							x = [1:10];  y = [4 15 7 17 8 19:23];





							%
						</input>
					</sage>
				</p>
			</sidebyside>

			<solution>

				<p>
					In case you missed any changes, let's go over them.
					<aside>
						<p>
							Notes:
							<ul>
								<li>default line width = 1.</li>
								<li><c>r</c> is an appreviation for 'red' and you could have typed <c>red</c> for the same effect.</li>
								<li>some options require single quotes, such as <c>'--'</c>. Be aware of this if you see any errors.</li>
							</ul>
						</p>
					</aside>
					<ul>
						<li><c>'LineWidth',3</c> in <c>plot(x,y,'LineWidth',3)</c> increased the line's width to 3.</li> 
						<li><c>'--'</c> in <c>plot(x,y,'--','LineWidth',3)</c> changed the solid line to a dashed line.</li> 
						<li><c>'&gt;'</c> in <c>plot(x,y,'--&gt;','LineWidth',3)</c> added the triangle symbol to each point.</li>
						<li><c>'r'</c> in <c>plot(x,y,'--&gt;r','LineWidth',3)</c> changed the color to red.</li>
						<li><c>title('My plot')</c> added the title to the top of plot.</li> 
						<li><c>xlim([0,11])</c> changed the range of the <m>x</m> values.</li> 
						<li><c>ylim([0,11])</c> changed the range of the <m>y</m> values.</li> 
						<li><c>text(7,15,'My function')</c> added text to the point <m>(7,5)</m>.</li> 
					</ul>
				</p>

				<p>
					All of the commands combined, as
					<program language="matlab">
						<input>
							x = [1:10];  y = [4 15 7 17 8 19:23]; 
							plot(x,y,'--&gt;b','LineWidth',3)
							title('My plot')
							xlim([0,11])
							ylim([0,30])
							text(7,15,'My function')
						</input>
					</program>
				</p>

				<p>
					produces the plot:
				</p>

				<image source="figures/matlab_plot2.png" />

			</solution>

		</example>

	</paragraphs>

</section>